      <!-- Care Tips -->
      <div class="card">
        <h2>10 Houseplant Watering Tips</h2>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>1. Check the soil first</strong><p>Stick your finger 1 inch into the soil. If it's dry, water. If moist, wait. This is more reliable than following a strict schedule.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>2. Water in the morning</strong><p>Morning watering lets excess moisture evaporate during the day, reducing the risk of root rot and fungal diseases.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>3. Use room temperature water</strong><p>Cold water can shock tropical plant roots. Let tap water sit for 30 minutes or use lukewarm water for sensitive plants.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>4. Water deeply, not often</strong><p>Soak the soil until water drains from the bottom. This encourages deep root growth. Light, frequent watering leads to shallow roots.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>5. Ensure proper drainage</strong><p>Always use pots with drainage holes. Standing water is the #1 cause of root rot. Use a saucer and empty it after 30 minutes.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>6. Adjust for seasons</strong><p>Reduce watering by 25-50% in winter. Plants grow slower and use less water. Increase in summer when evaporation is higher.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>7. Humidity matters</strong><p>Group tropical plants together to boost local humidity. Misting helps temporarily, but a pebble tray or humidifier is more effective.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>8. Know your pot material</strong><p>Terracotta is porous and dries out faster than plastic or ceramic. Adjust watering frequency based on your pot material.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>9. Watch for warning signs</strong><p>Yellowing leaves = overwatering. Brown crispy edges = underwatering. Wilting can mean either — check the soil to tell.</p></div>
        <div class="tip-item"><strong>10. Bottom watering works</strong><p>Place the pot in a tray of water for 20-30 minutes. The soil wicks up moisture evenly. Great for plants that dislike wet foliage.</p></div>
      </div>

      <!-- SEO Content -->
      <div class="seo-content">
        <h2>How to Create a Plant Watering Schedule</h2>
        <p>A plant watering schedule helps you keep track of when each of your houseplants needs water. Different plants have different needs based on their species, the amount of light they receive, the size of their pot, and the current season. This tool automates the process by calculating an adjusted watering frequency for each plant based on these factors.</p>

        <h2>Understanding Watering Frequency</h2>
        <p>Most houseplants fall into three watering categories: frequent (every 3-5 days for moisture-loving plants like ferns and calatheas), moderate (every 7-10 days for most tropical plants like pothos and monsteras), and infrequent (every 14-21 days for succulents, cacti, and snake plants). This base frequency is then adjusted based on environmental factors.</p>

        <h3>How location affects watering</h3>
        <p>Plants near windows receive more light and heat, causing soil to dry faster. A plant on a bright windowsill may need water twice as often as the same plant on a dim shelf. Bathrooms have higher humidity which slows evaporation, while outdoor plants may need daily watering in summer heat.</p>

        <h3>How pot size affects watering</h3>
        <p>Small pots (2-4 inches) have less soil volume and dry out quickly — sometimes in just 2-3 days. Large pots (10+ inches) retain moisture much longer and may only need watering every 10-14 days. The pot material also matters: terracotta is porous and breathes, drying soil faster than plastic or glazed ceramic pots.</p>

        <h3>Seasonal adjustments</h3>
        <p>During spring and summer, most houseplants are actively growing and need more frequent watering. In fall and winter, growth slows dramatically. Reduce watering by 25-50% during the colder months. Heating systems can also dry indoor air, which may partially offset the reduced water needs.</p>

        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <h3>How often should I water my houseplants?</h3>
        <p>It depends on the plant species, pot size, light exposure, humidity, and season. Most tropical houseplants need water every 7-10 days. Succulents and cacti need water every 14-21 days. During winter, reduce frequency by 25-50%.</p>

        <h3>How do I know if I'm overwatering?</h3>
        <p>Signs include yellowing leaves, mushy stems, mold on soil, fungus gnats, and a sour smell. Always check if the top inch of soil is dry before watering, and ensure pots have drainage holes.</p>

        <h3>Should I water more in summer or winter?</h3>
        <p>Water more frequently in spring and summer when plants are actively growing. Reduce frequency in fall and winter when growth slows and evaporation decreases.</p>

        <h3>Does pot size affect watering frequency?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Small pots dry out faster and need more frequent watering. Large pots retain moisture longer. Terracotta pots dry faster than plastic or ceramic.</p>

        <h3>What's the best time of day to water?</h3>
        <p>Morning is best. It allows excess moisture to evaporate during the day, reducing the risk of fungal diseases and root rot. Avoid watering at night.</p>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    // Plant database: 40+ common houseplants
    var DB = [
